        <div id="content" class="md-content ">

            <div id="edit-toolbar-placeholder"></div>
        <div class="md-topic-alternate-titles font-sans-ui">
        <strong>Alternative titles: </strong>
        nerve cell; neurone</div><div class="md-content-wrapper  topic-content">
                <article class="content-body font-sans-ui has-media" vocab="http://schema.org" resource="http://semantic.britannica.com/accepted_headword/core/410669/neuron" typeof="Article">
            <meta property="url" href="/science/neuron" />
            <meta property="name" content="neuron" />

            <!--[TOC-PLACEHOLDER]--><section id="toc410669main" class="eb-topic-section" data-level="intro"><p><b><span class="srTitle">Neuron</span></b><b>,</b>&nbsp;also called <span class="alternate">nerve cell</span>,&nbsp;
    <a href="/science/neuron/images-videos/Neurons-which-are-supported-by-glial-cells-such-as-astrocytes/118260" class="bps-assembly-container media-overlay-link" data-id="118260" data-type="image" data-ytrk="76"><span class="md-assembly-content"><img alt="astrocyte: neurons and astrocytes [Credit: Institute for Stem Cell Research/Getty Images]" src="http://media-1.web.britannica.com/eb-media/19/123919-004-652698E3.jpg" width="447" height="450"><span class="md-assembly-thumb-caption"><span class="md-assembly-thumb-title">astrocyte: neurons and astrocytes</span><span class="md-assembly-thumb-credit">Institute for Stem Cell Research/Getty Images</span></span></span></a>basic <a data-ytrk="/548" href="/science/cell-biology"><span property="about" href="http://semantic.britannica.com/accepted_headword/core/101396/cell">cell</span></a> of the <a data-ytrk="/548" href="/science/nervous-system"><span property="about" href="http://semantic.britannica.com/accepted_headword/core/409665/nervous-system">nervous system</span></a> in vertebrates and most invertebrates from the level of the <a data-ytrk="/548" href="/animal/cnidarian"><span property="about" href="http://semantic.britannica.com/accepted_headword/core/122750/cnidarian">cnidarians</span></a> (e.g., corals, jellyfish) upward. A typical neuron has a cell body containing a <a data-ytrk="/548" href="/science/nucleus-biology"><span property="about" href="http://semantic.britannica.com/accepted_headword/core/422009/nucleus">nucleus</span></a> and two or more long fibres. Impulses are carried along one or more of these fibres, called <a name="ref252218" id="ref252218"></a><a data-ytrk="/548" href="/science/dendrite-neuron"><span property="about" href="http://semantic.britannica.com/accepted_headword/core/157558/dendrite">dendrites</span></a>, to the cell body; in higher nervous systems, only one fibre, the <a name="ref252219" id="ref252219"></a><a data-ytrk="/548" href="/science/axon"><span property="about" href="http://semantic.britannica.com/accepted_headword/core/46342/axon">axon</span></a>, carries the impulse away from the cell body. Bundles of fibres from neurons are held together by connective <a data-ytrk="/548" href="/science/tissue"><span property="about" href="http://semantic.britannica.com/accepted_headword/core/597008/tissue">tissue</span></a> and form nerves. Some nerves in large vertebrates are several feet long. A <a name="ref252220" id="ref252220"></a><a data-ytrk="/548" href="/science/sensory-neuron"><span property="about" href="http://semantic.britannica.com/accepted_headword/core/534822/sensory-neuron">sensory neuron</span></a> transmits impulses from a <a data-ytrk="/548" href="/science/receptor-nerve-ending"><span property="about" href="http://semantic.britannica.com/accepted_headword/core/493438/receptor">receptor</span></a>, such as those in the <a data-ytrk="/548" href="/science/human-eye"><span property="about" href="http://semantic.britannica.com/accepted_headword/core/1688997/human-eye">eye</span></a> or <a data-ytrk="/548" href="/science/ear"><span property="about" href="http://semantic.britannica.com/accepted_headword/core/175622/human-ear">ear</span></a>, to a more central location in the nervous system, such as the spinal cord or <a data-ytrk="/548" href="/science/brain"><span property="about" href="http://semantic.britannica.com/accepted_headword/core/77269/brain">brain</span></a>. A <a name="ref252221" id="ref252221"></a><a data-ytrk="/548" href="/science/motor-neuron"><span property="about" href="http://semantic.britannica.com/accepted_headword/core/394313/motor-neuron">motor neuron</span></a> transmits impulses from a central area of the nervous system to an <a data-ytrk="/548" href="/science/effector-anatomy"><span property="about" href="http://semantic.britannica.com/accepted_headword/core/179983/effector">effector</span></a>, such as a muscle.</p><!--[MEDIA-STRIP]--><!--[END-1ST-PARA]--></section></article>

